01:30.239 --> 01:32.108
So what? I'm a hero.

01:32.141 --> 01:33.610
You used a slur, dude.

01:33.643 --> 01:35.145
That's like a hate crime.

01:35.179 --> 01:36.214
Yeah, that's hateful speech, man.

01:36.247 --> 01:37.748
- You really can't...
- Yeah, but he saved his life.

01:37.780 --> 01:39.115
Yeah, but you can't say
that word anymore.

01:39.149 --> 01:40.617
So, which is it?

02:04.783 --> 02:06.506
<i>You are entitled to nothing!</i>

02:06.556 --> 02:08.169
Listen, motion to present

02:08.202 --> 02:09.551
articles of confederation.

02:09.584 --> 02:10.597
- Motion denied.
- Oh...

02:10.607 --> 02:12.417
Shut up, bitch.
You don't deserve anything.

02:12.450 --> 02:14.491
Excuse me. Hey. Can I help you?

02:14.525 --> 02:16.370
Okay, look, well, usually,
we're a pretty reasonable crew.

02:16.402 --> 02:17.984
- Yeah, right? I mean...
- Yeah.

02:18.015 --> 02:19.202
...we have our differences,
but we settle them in house.

02:19.235 --> 02:20.519
- Sure.
- We have a good process.

02:20.553 --> 02:21.903
There's filibusters, the whole thing.

02:21.935 --> 02:23.878
- No.
- This one's a doozy.

02:23.912 --> 02:25.196
- Yeah, this one we can't do in-house.
- We can't... we can't...

02:25.229 --> 02:27.205
That's why I wanted to
bring in a third party.

02:27.238 --> 02:29.642
Someone to hear us out and
deliver a final verdict.

02:29.675 --> 02:30.629
- That's you, guy.
- Yeah, that's... you.

02:30.663 --> 02:31.617
That's you.

02:31.651 --> 02:34.153
Because a great injustice
has occurred, okay?

02:34.187 --> 02:35.570
Frank committed a hate crime.

02:35.603 --> 02:36.986
I saved your life.

02:37.020 --> 02:39.128
- But you used a slur!
- It was a slur.

02:39.159 --> 02:40.674
- That's...
- You'd be dead if I didn't!

02:40.708 --> 02:41.893
Okay, okay, I think I'm getting it.

02:41.927 --> 02:43.706
You want me to figure out whether or not

02:43.737 --> 02:44.858
a hate crime's been committed?

02:44.891 --> 02:46.209
What?

02:46.240 --> 02:47.196
- No.
- No, no, no, no.

02:47.228 --> 02:48.414
- Way off. Way off.
- No, no, no, no, no.

02:48.447 --> 02:50.423
Oh, no, but, no,
it's not about that at all.

02:50.456 --> 02:52.236
Yeah, it's about this.

02:52.267 --> 02:54.935
A two-dollar scratcher lottery ticket.

02:54.969 --> 02:56.188
- Mm-hmm.
- Yeah.

02:56.220 --> 02:58.888
Y-You've hired an arbitration attorney

02:58.920 --> 03:00.765
to figure out which of you is entitled

03:00.798 --> 03:01.984
to a two-dollar scratcher?

03:02.015 --> 03:02.971
- Now you're getting it.
- Me.

03:03.003 --> 03:04.651
- He's getting it.
- Now he gets it.

03:04.683 --> 03:06.725
The thing is, each one of us
feels that we're entitled

03:06.759 --> 03:08.043
to that ticket, and we need you

03:08.076 --> 03:09.658
- to tell us who it belongs to.
- Yeah.

03:09.690 --> 03:12.060
Why don't you scratch it
and see if it's worthless,

03:12.094 --> 03:14.598
and then you wouldn't have
to go through all of this?

03:14.629 --> 03:15.650
- Okay, so he's not getting it.
- What?!

03:15.684 --> 03:16.936
- Is he serious?
- Do you not want a job?

03:16.968 --> 03:18.812
Hold on. Is it Phil? Is your name Phil?

03:18.846 --> 03:20.460
- Yeah, Phil, yeah.
- It is Phil?

03:20.491 --> 03:21.547
It's Phil.

03:21.578 --> 03:23.423
This ticket represents hope, okay?

03:23.456 --> 03:25.038
Potential... yeah?

03:25.069 --> 03:26.388
Promise.

03:26.420 --> 03:29.845
The very foundation upon
which this group rests, eh?

03:29.878 --> 03:30.833
- Yes.
- And that hope

03:30.866 --> 03:32.382
belongs to me.

03:32.414 --> 03:34.127
It belongs to me, you son of a bitch!

03:36.466 --> 03:37.981
Please, stop.

03:38.012 --> 03:40.845
Each of you will have an
opportunity to plead your case.

03:40.879 --> 03:43.776
The only rule I have is that
you each treat each other

03:43.809 --> 03:46.938
with respect and common courtesy.

03:46.971 --> 03:49.276
Do we all agree to those terms?

03:51.285 --> 03:53.492
Well, we would like to thank you so much

03:53.525 --> 03:55.370
for taking our case so last-minute.

03:55.402 --> 03:57.147
The other guy was not our style.

03:57.179 --> 03:59.386
Well, I'm very happy to do so.

03:59.419 --> 04:01.758
I do have a few questions.

04:01.792 --> 04:03.075
- Fire away. - Yup.
- Of course, yeah.

04:03.109 --> 04:06.962
Now, the ticket in question,
uh, who purchased it?

04:06.994 --> 04:07.951
- Me! Thank you.
- Well...

04:07.983 --> 04:09.005
That was me, and that's why

04:09.038 --> 04:10.651
- this whole thing is so cut and dry.
- It's...

04:10.684 --> 04:11.935
Hold on. I purchased the ticket,

04:11.968 --> 04:14.537
and therefore the ticket belongs to me.

04:14.570 --> 04:17.930
<i>I actually bought the ticket
a couple of weeks ago.</i>

04:17.961 --> 04:20.661
<i>But I didn't realize it was
gonna be so goddamn blustery</i>

04:20.694 --> 04:21.767
<i>that afternoon.</i>

04:22.738 --> 04:25.076
<i>And as I was putting
my book into my purse,</i>

04:25.107 --> 04:27.644
<i>the ticket flew out and
landed on the ground.</i>

04:29.784 --> 04:31.597
So, you purchased the ticket
two weeks ago.

04:31.630 --> 04:32.684
I did.

04:32.717 --> 04:34.990
And why hadn't you
scratched the ticket yet?

04:35.021 --> 04:37.361
Oh... well, that's because

04:37.393 --> 04:39.007
nobody ever wins those tickets, right?

04:39.039 --> 04:40.786
But as long as you don't scratch it,

04:40.817 --> 04:42.103
then you're not a loser.

04:42.136 --> 04:45.199
You know, in fact, you're a winner.

04:45.230 --> 04:46.582
Potentially.

04:46.614 --> 04:48.557
- God, Dee...
- That is so sad!

04:48.590 --> 04:49.546
- It's so pathetic.
- What are...

04:49.579 --> 04:50.962
- It is pathetic.
- So sad.

04:50.993 --> 04:52.313
What are you talking... You just said

04:52.346 --> 04:53.893
this exact same thing,
like, ten minutes ago,

04:53.926 --> 04:54.913
talking about how the ticket

04:54.946 --> 04:55.935
represented hope and all that bullshit.

04:55.967 --> 04:58.701
Somehow coming from you,
it just came off so sad.

04:58.734 --> 05:00.579
Well, hold on a second.
Motion for sub-arbitration

05:00.612 --> 05:02.226
to determine whether or not that's sad.

05:02.258 --> 05:03.806
Motion accepted. All in favor?

05:03.839 --> 05:04.794
Aye.

05:04.827 --> 05:05.946
Motion passed. It's sad, Dee.

05:05.980 --> 05:07.099
I'd also like to point out

05:07.132 --> 05:09.208
that while Dee's version is the truth,

05:09.240 --> 05:10.886
it's not the whole truth.

05:10.920 --> 05:14.642
<i>Why don't we talk about the
contents of Dee's purse?</i>

05:15.659 --> 05:17.112
<i>The scratcher ticket,
the candy sour worms,</i>

05:17.145 --> 05:18.165
<i>the pack of cigarettes.</i>

05:18.198 --> 05:20.966
<i>Now, what I want to know is...</i>

05:20.998 --> 05:23.565
<i>how can a woman who makes
less than minimum wage</i>

05:23.599 --> 05:26.037
<i>afford such impulse buys?</i>

05:26.069 --> 05:28.869
So, you're smoking now, Dee?

05:28.901 --> 05:30.383
Is this about your weight?

05:30.416 --> 05:32.689
Because if it is,
you're already too bony.

05:32.722 --> 05:34.335
No, I don't think so.
I mean, I think you're

05:34.369 --> 05:35.455
getting pretty tubby
in the midsection area.

05:35.488 --> 05:36.872
- What?
- Like a bird.

05:36.905 --> 05:38.222
No, no, that's fine.

05:38.255 --> 05:40.922
Her hands are becoming a
major problem for me though.

05:40.955 --> 05:42.735
I have Parkinson's disease.

05:42.767 --> 05:44.018
What?

05:44.051 --> 05:46.851
Well, at least I have a 46% chance

05:46.884 --> 05:49.651
of getting Parkinson's disease,
according to a DNA test I took.

05:49.683 --> 05:52.351
The medical journal was
because I'm trying to learn

05:52.384 --> 05:54.557
as much as I can about this, you know?

05:54.591 --> 05:55.744
And, you guys, according to that,

05:55.775 --> 05:57.554
smoking can reduce your risk of...

05:57.588 --> 05:59.661
Oh, my God, who gives a shit?!

05:59.694 --> 06:01.441
- What?
- Dee, this isn't about whether or not

06:01.473 --> 06:03.451
you have some horrific
neurological disease

06:03.483 --> 06:05.262
or whether or not your
hands are the right size.

06:05.294 --> 06:07.403
They are, by the way,
but your elbows are a mess.

06:07.434 --> 06:08.587
They're too sharp.

06:08.621 --> 06:09.510
I don't like it. They're stabbing me.

06:09.541 --> 06:10.892
- That's what it is.
- You got it.

06:10.924 --> 06:12.540
That's not the point,
that's not the point.

06:12.573 --> 06:16.492
The point is:
how can you actually afford to smoke?

06:16.524 --> 06:18.467
You see, Dee and I had a deal.

06:18.500 --> 06:19.620
I give her money for coffee

06:19.654 --> 06:21.266
every morning on the way to work.

06:21.300 --> 06:23.836
<i>And she's instructed to give</i>

06:23.867 --> 06:25.647
<i>a very generous tip
to the cashier, Cassie.</i>

06:27.557 --> 06:30.225
<i>"This is from my boss, Dennis."</i>

06:30.257 --> 06:33.551
<i>Now, this establishes both
generosity and authority.</i>

06:33.584 --> 06:35.264
Possibly a little dominance.

06:35.296 --> 06:36.812
It's all a very choreographed dance

06:36.844 --> 06:38.030
between two soon-to-be lovers.

06:39.249 --> 06:40.007
Ah...

06:40.500 --> 06:42.016
Cassie's underage.

06:42.454 --> 06:44.385
No, no, no, what-what?
What are you talking about?

06:44.385 --> 06:46.133
Cassie is not underage.

06:46.165 --> 06:48.010
Cassie is 21 years old.

06:48.043 --> 06:50.644
<i>So, the champagne I was purchasing</i>

06:50.676 --> 06:53.049
<i>was to celebrate her
legal drinking status.</i>

06:53.081 --> 06:54.629
<i>And to honor her full maturity.</i>

06:56.046 --> 06:57.955
You see, I was waiting
for Cassie to mature.

06:57.988 --> 06:59.635
You know, much like an IRA.

06:59.668 --> 07:02.106
Y-You put the money in, then you wait.

07:02.138 --> 07:04.708
And then you make a hefty withdrawal.

07:06.913 --> 07:07.999
Okay, yeah, sure.

07:08.032 --> 07:10.635
Before full maturity, yeah, ew.

07:10.668 --> 07:11.885
Yeah, but weren't you just saying

07:11.919 --> 07:14.027
that you were doing
deposits before maturity?

07:14.059 --> 07:15.838
Uh, no, no, no, no.
See, that's where you're wrong.

07:15.871 --> 07:18.309
No, I was, uh,
between the ages of 18 and 21,

07:18.342 --> 07:19.791
simply making investments.

07:19.822 --> 07:21.338
But not for early deposits?

07:21.371 --> 07:23.150
Well, deposits
are part of the withdrawal.

07:23.182 --> 07:25.586
Sometimes I can't make a deposit at all.

07:25.619 --> 07:27.102
Ugh, come on, man.

07:27.134 --> 07:28.091
Just...

07:28.122 --> 07:29.407
Okay, just to be clear:

07:29.441 --> 07:30.857
a deposit's a load, right?

07:30.889 --> 07:32.569
- Yeah.
- Well, yeah, yeah.

07:32.601 --> 07:33.558
That's not what I'm talking about.

07:33.590 --> 07:35.105
No, it's a totally different...

07:35.138 --> 07:36.751
- Are you sure?
- No, with my... no.

07:36.784 --> 07:39.057
Look, not in this particular case,
it's not a lo...

07:39.090 --> 07:40.079
It's-it's...

07:42.318 --> 07:43.767
Yeah, it's a load.

07:43.798 --> 07:45.248
- Yeah. I mean, yeah.
- But that's not the point!

07:45.281 --> 07:46.467
That's not the point! The point is:

07:46.500 --> 07:48.543
Dee has no rightful
claim to that ticket,

07:48.574 --> 07:50.023
and I'll prove it.

07:50.057 --> 07:51.769
<i>You see, yesterday,</i>

07:51.801 --> 07:53.482
<i>after noticing the
contents of her purse,</i>

07:53.515 --> 07:56.182
<i>I decided to follow her this morning.</i>

07:56.216 --> 07:57.401
<i>Cassie never gets her tip,</i>

07:57.434 --> 07:59.049
does she, Dee?

07:59.080 --> 08:01.024
No. Because I refuse to tip for coffee.

08:01.056 --> 08:03.000
- I think it's dumb.
- Uh-huh.

08:03.033 --> 08:04.514
So if you were buying circus peanuts

08:04.547 --> 08:05.930
and candy sour worms and cigarettes,

08:05.963 --> 08:07.577
I think we all know what that means

08:07.610 --> 08:10.574
about the ticket in question, don't we?

08:12.187 --> 08:13.967
I don't. Do you know?

08:13.999 --> 08:15.646
- No.
- Totally lost.

08:15.679 --> 08:18.183
That means she bought it with my money!

08:18.215 --> 08:20.060
So, technically, that ticket is mine!

08:20.092 --> 08:21.740
Okay, okay, okay.

08:21.772 --> 08:24.177
Now, let me sum up the facts thus far.

08:24.208 --> 08:26.317
Miss Reynolds bought the ticket

08:26.350 --> 08:27.800
with Mr. Reynolds' money.

08:27.833 --> 08:30.270
But Mr. MacDonald
currently possesses it.

08:30.301 --> 08:33.760
Correct.
But I deserve it, and here's why.

08:33.792 --> 08:35.933
<i>There we were, right?</i>

08:35.966 --> 08:37.613
<i>We were just walking down the street,</i>

08:37.645 --> 08:38.898
<i>minding our own business.</i>

08:38.931 --> 08:41.533
<i>I'd just spotted the
perfect pile of dog shit,</i>

08:41.565 --> 08:42.553
<i>and naturally I stepped in it.</i>

08:42.586 --> 08:43.673
- What?
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

08:43.705 --> 08:45.320
Okay, I'm a little confused.

08:45.353 --> 08:48.318
